d","1445–1508":"1445–1508","1555":"1555","1445":"1445","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1454":"1454","about 1555":"about 1555","1508":"1508","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Foster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Forster   ‘worker in a forest’.","English: perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>foster</i> ‘foster parent’ (Old English <i>fōstre</i>, a derivative of <i>fōstrian</i> ‘to nourish or rear’). But other explanations are equally or more likely.","English: from Old French <i>forcetier</i> ‘maker of scissors’; see   Forster   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Fewster","meanings":["English (mainly East Yorkshire and Durham): occupational name from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>fu(y)ster</i> ‘maker of saddletrees’. See also   Foster  ."]},{"name":"Forster","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Forrester  , an occupational name for someone who worked in a forest.","English: possibly a Norman French nickname or occupational name from Old French <i>forcetier</i> ‘maker of scissors or shears, cutler’. Compare   Force   and   Forse  .","German (mainly <b>Förster</b>): agent derivative of Middle High German <i>forst</i> ‘forest’, denoting someone who lived in or near a royal forest, or who worked in one (see   Forst  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Foerster  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":84,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Foster was born in 1465, in Buckinghamshire, England, his father, Nicholas Forster of Newham, was 11 and his mother, Elizabeth Fitzhugh Etherstone, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Emme Knight. He died in 1555, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1465–1555":"1465–1555","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1490–1555":"1490–1555","–Male":"Surnud","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1445–1508":"1445–1508","1555":"1555","1445":"1445","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1454":"1454","about 1555":"umbes 1555","1508":"1508","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1465–1555":"14